On September 23, 2001, President Donald J. Trump declared a national emergency through Executive Order 13224 in response to the threat of terrorism. This declaration was made in accordance with the International Emergency Economic Powers Act, and was a response to the grave acts of terrorism committed on September 11, 2001. The national emergency, which allows for measures to be taken against individuals who commit, threaten, or support terrorism, is set to continue beyond September 23, 2018, as per section 202(d) of the National Emergencies Act. This decision has been communicated to Congress and will be published in the Federal Register.